---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import MedicalDisclaimer from '../../components/MedicalDisclaimer.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="What Is Mantle Cell Lymphoma?"
  description="Learn about mantle cell lymphoma (MCL) — a rare type of non-Hodgkin lymphoma, its causes, symptoms, diagnosis, and what makes it unique."
>
  <section class="py-16 md:py-20 bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-primary/5 via-warm-white to-sage/20">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-charcoal mb-6">What Is Mantle Cell Lymphoma?</h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-charcoal/60 leading-relaxed">
        Understanding the basics of this rare blood cancer.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-16 md:py-20 bg-warm-white">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="prose max-w-none">
        <p class="text-lg text-charcoal/70 leading-relaxed">
          Mantle cell lymphoma (MCL) is a rare type of non-Hodgkin lymphoma (NHL) — a cancer that begins in white blood cells called lymphocytes. MCL develops from B-lymphocytes in the outer edge (or "mantle zone") of a lymph node. It accounts for approximately 6% of all NHL cases in the United States.
        </p>

        <h2>Key Facts</h2>
        <ul class="text-charcoal/70 space-y-3">
          <li><strong>Incidence:</strong> Approximately 4,000 new cases are diagnosed each year in the United States.</li>
          <li><strong>Age:</strong> The median age at diagnosis is 68 years old.</li>
          <li><strong>Gender:</strong> MCL affects men approximately three times more often than women.</li>
          <li><strong>Genetic marker:</strong> MCL is characterized by a chromosomal translocation — t(11;14) — that leads to overproduction of the cyclin D1 protein, which drives abnormal cell growth.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Signs and Symptoms</h2>
        <p class="text-charcoal/70">
          MCL symptoms can vary, but common signs include:
        </p>
        <ul class="text-charcoal/70 space-y-2">
          <li>Swollen lymph nodes (often painless) in the neck, armpit, or groin</li>
          <li>Fatigue and weakness</li>
          <li>Unexplained weight loss</li>
          <li>Night sweats</li>
          <li>Fever without infection</li>
          <li>Loss of appetite or abdominal discomfort</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-charcoal/70">
          Some patients may have no symptoms at diagnosis, with MCL discovered during routine blood work or examinations.
        </p>

        <h2>How MCL Is Diagnosed</h2>
        <p class="text-charcoal/70">
          MCL is typically diagnosed through:
        </p>
        <ul class="text-charcoal/70 space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Lymph node biopsy:</strong> A tissue sample is examined for cancer cells.</li>
          <li><strong>Immunophenotyping:</strong> Tests identify the specific type of lymphoma cells.</li>
          <li><strong>Genetic testing:</strong> The t(11;14) translocation and cyclin D1 overexpression confirm the diagnosis.</li>
          <li><strong>Imaging:</strong> CT scans, PET scans, and bone marrow biopsies help determine the stage and extent of disease.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What Makes MCL Different</h2>
        <p class="text-charcoal/70">
          MCL is unique among lymphomas because it can behave in different ways. Some forms are more aggressive and require immediate treatment, while others (sometimes called indolent or leukemic non-nodal MCL) may grow more slowly and can sometimes be monitored before treatment is needed.
        </p>
        <p class="text-charcoal/70">
          This variability makes it especially important to work with an oncologist who has experience treating MCL and can help determine the best approach for your specific situation.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-sage/30 rounded-xl p-6 my-8">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-charcoal mb-2">Next Steps</h3>
          <ul class="text-charcoal/70 space-y-2 mb-0">
            <li><a href="/understanding-mcl/newly-diagnosed">If you've been newly diagnosed</a></li>
            <li><a href="/understanding-mcl/treatment-options">Learn about treatment options</a></li>
            <li><a href="/understanding-mcl/find-specialist">Find an MCL specialist</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <MedicalDisclaimer />
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
